      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bear or Human: Who's Invading Whom?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Glenn C Hurowitz letter opposes New Jersey plan to allow hunting for black bears (S),</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If the New Jersey Fish and Game Council considers cohabitation between black bears and humans impossible (news article, June 3), it should encourage development policies that reduce human-wildlife interaction rather than sanctioning a renewed hunting assault on the already limited population of black bears in the state.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If the New Jersey Fish and Game Council considers cohabitation between black bears and humans impossible (news article, June 3), it should encourage development policies that reduce human-wildlife interaction rather than sanctioning a renewed hunting assault on the already limited population of black bears in the state.</p>
        <p>The New Jersey black bear population has made a remarkable comeback from near-zero levels. It would be a shame if the animals were now made to pay with their lives for the growing sprawl that brings humans into closer contact with nature. It is not the bears that are the intruders, but those few suburbanites who are unwilling to accept and enjoy nature in all but its most sanitized form.</p>
        <p>GLENN C. HUROWITZ  Briarcliff Manor, N.Y., June 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
